    <h2> Introduction</h2>
  <p>On this page you will find out more <strong>About</strong> the <strong>FreeBMD project</strong> thorough a series of questions-and-answers. Note: more detailed information, mainly relevant to people transcribing the GRO indexes, rather than searching them, may be found on the original FreeBMD site.</p> 
  <p class="islet islet--bordered">At a later date, we will also move these transcriber’s questions-and-answers onto this site.</p>  

  <h2> Questions and Answers</h2>
  <h3 id="whyNecessary">Why is the FreeBMD Project necessary?</h3>
   <p>The Civil Registration indexes for England and Wales - which is what the <strong>FreeBMD Project</strong> covers — have been freely available from a variety of non-electronic sources for some time now. Small parts of the indexes have already been placed on the Internet.</p>
 <p>In the wider context of the UK and Ireland: The Civil Registration indexes for Scotland, which are separate from those of England and Wales, have already been placed online on a pay-per-view basis at <a href="http://www.scotlandspeople.gov.uk" target="_blank">Scotland's People (opens in a new tab)</a>.  Irish Civil Registrations are available without charge at <a href="https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/civil-search.jsp" target="_blank"> Irish Genealogy (opens in a new tab)</a> for the whole island of Ireland, excluding the counties that from 1922 onwards are in Northern Ireland. Records from Northern Ireland both before and after 1922 are available on a pay-per-view basis at <a href="https://geni.nidirect.gov.uk" target="_blank">Northern Ireland General Register Office (opens in a new tab)</a>. </p> 
  <p>Usually available on microfilm or microfiche, the Civil Registration indexes for England and Wales can be illegible due to the varying quality of microreproduction. Currently, there is no centrally-available method for rapidly searching the indexes. They were originally issued every quarter-year and within each quarter are arranged alphabetically by surname. From January 1984 they were issued annually. However, these indexes as a whole have not been consolidated into a master index. Furthermore, older marriage records were not at that time cross-indexed to paired-spouses, making them extremely tedious to use. (However, see <a href="#GroComputerise">Aren't the GRO already computerising the indexes?</a> for an update on the GRO’s re-indexing project).</p>
  <p>The creation of a freely accessible Internet-based database of the Civil Registration index information coupled with a free search engine facility will greatly enhance a researcher's ability to quickly and easily locate all the index entries of potential relevance.</p>
  <p>Inevitably, there are some records that are partially illegible. FreeBMD’s transcribers ensure that we clearly show what we <em>can read</em> and what is a <em>best-guess</em> (see <a href="/cms/help/more-about-searching#unreadable">how we indicate unreadable records </a> for more details). They are searchable, but as a researcher you may need to do further work to identify the specific record, taking into account any illegibility. </p>
   <p>In addition, FreeBMD carries out various quality and consistency checks during every update of its data-base (on a rolling four-week cycle). It identifies individual records that appear to be internally-inconsistent —  this may show up as an inconsistency between a page-number, its expected range of values and the given Registration District. In the case of a record marked as <em>possibly inconsistent</em>, FreeBMD’s consistency-checks may help the researcher: work out what the record <em>should be</em>; obtain the correct certificate from the GRO; and the eventual correction of such records — or a by a user-submitted Postem.</p>

   <h3 id="howOperate">How does the FreeBMD Project operate? </h3>
   <p>Using volunteers throughout the world, the transcription of the Civil Registration index is co-ordinated, under the guidance of the FreeBMD Project leadership, by a Volunteer Co-ordinator and various volunteer Syndicate Leaders. So, the FreeBMD Project makes orderly progress towards its goal.</p>
  <p>Data entered into the database will be available for access through the search facility. The database is updated periodically (on a rolling four-week cycle) with the latest available data. Data is also be accepted from previous extractions by those performing one-name studies.</p>
  <p>Data is accepted in a variety of formats, including a <a href="https://www.freebmd.org.uk/format.shtml" target="_blank">simple text format — as specified on the original FreeBMD site (opens in a new tab)</a>. These submission files can be prepared off-line using basic word-processing, spreadsheet or database management software. Special transcription software is available from FreeBMD — on the old site — to assist with the task of transcribing pages of the index.</p>
  <p>Ultimately, all data will be entered at least twice by independent transcribers in order to improve the accuracy.</p>

 <h3 id="ownsRunsFreebmd">Who owns the FreeBMD database and runs FreeBMD?</h3>
  <p>Authority to reproduce the information for free access on the Internet was originally granted to the FreeBMD Project leadership. In order to ensure the long term stability of the project, and to gain access to grant funding, the project leaders established FreeBMD as a trust in June 2002.</p> 
  <p> In 2014 we changed the name to Free UK Genealogy which better reflects the aims of the charity. In 2017 Free UK Genealogy became a Charitable Incorporated Organization.</p>
  <p>Free UK Genealogy is committed to supporting the transcription of public records and making these available as free access public databases. We are registered with the Charity Commissioners as Free UK Genealogy CIO, Number 1167484; and our <a href="https://www.freeukgenealogy.org.uk/files/Documents/Free-UK-Genealogy-Foundation-CIOConstitution.pdf" target="_blank"> Constitution can be viewed on-line (Pdf opens in a new Tab)</a>. </p> 
  <p> All rights in data submitted to the site are now owned by Free UK Genealogy CIO. The names of the trustees of our charity can be found <a href="http://www.freeukgenealogy.org.uk/about/trustees/" target="_blank">on the Free UK Genealogy website (opens in a new Tab)</a>. </p>
  
  <h3 id="GroComputerise">Aren't the GRO already computerising the indexes?</h3>
  <p>The GRO has re-indexed all birth records up to one hundred years ago; and this includes adding the mother’s maiden name to the earlier — prior to July to September 1911 — records. These and more recent births (from 1984 to a year or two before present), which were created digitally, can be searched.</p>
   <p>They have not re-indexed their marriage records, so you cannot search, but you can order copies of marriage certificates, having previously found the GRO Index reference on FreeBMD, or one of the pay-to-view sites, etc.</p>
 <p>Death records have been re-indexed to 1957, and the records from 1984, created digitally, can also be searched.</p>
 <p class="islet islet--bordered"> The <a href="https://www.gro.gov.uk/gro/content/certificates/login.asp" target="_blank"> GRO site can be accessed here (opens in a new tab)</a>. You first need to Register yourself for an online account — by setting up a Username and Password — and then logon to do your search. At a minimum, you need to specify whether: your search is for a birth or a death record; specify a gender (male or female); and the expected year(s) of the event — exact to that year, plus or minus one year, or plus or minus two years. Note: you do not need to order a certificate to use the search facility.</p>
    <p class="push-half--bottom">The GRO Indexes (as of October 2021, to 2007 only) are available without charge at FamilySearch; and on several pay-to-view websites. Unfortunately, the other post-1984 indexes are not, at present, available free of charge on the internet but copies can be consulted on fiche free of charge in a small number of libraries: </p>
   <ul class="push-half--bottom">
      <li>Manchester City Library </li>
      <li>Birmingham Central Library </li>
      <li>Bridgend Reference and Information Library </li>
      <li>Plymouth Central Library </li>
      <li>City of Westminster Archives Centre </li>
      <li>London Metropolitan Archives </li>
      <li>The British Library </li>
   </ul>
  <p>These libraries also hold fiche indexes not available elsewhere or online civil partnerships from 2005 to 2020 and adopted children, up to 2019.</p>

  <h3 id="giveAccess">Couldn't the GRO give volunteers access to the source records? </h3>
  <p>In a word, <strong>No</strong>. It is actually illegal for anyone except the registrars to browse the source records (and even they are only allowed to do it within strict guidelines — which, sadly, do not include checking accuracy for us).</p>

  <h3 id="DPAcoversThis">Are the BMD indexes covered by Data Protection legislation? </h3>
  <p>Data Protection applies to information held about living individuals. The GRO information held by FreeBMD is publicly available and therefore not confidential in itself but FreeBMD still has to ensure that the information is held and used properly, hence the conditions of use and the restrictions on the search results page. (You can also <a href="/cms/terms-and-conditions" target="_blank">view them via this link (opens in a new tab</a>). FreeBMD, therefore, complies with the Data Protection Act 2018 (DPA 2018) and the General Data Protection Regulation (UK GDPR).</p>

  <p class="islet islet--bordered">You can find out more about these two Acts on the Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) web site. The <a href="https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-data-protection/" target="_blank"> Guide to Data Protection (opens in a new tab)</a>; and the <a href="https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/guide-to-data-protection/guide-to-the-general-data-protection-regulation-gdpr/" target="_blank"> General Data Protection Regulation (UK GDPR) (opens in a new Tab) </a> provide official ICO guidance.</p>
 <p> Our parent charity, Free UK Genealogy CIO is registered with the <a href="https://ico.org.uk" target="_blank"> Information Commissioner's Office (opens in new tab)</a>, under reference number Z7436529. </p>

  <h3 id="helpFundUs">How is the FreeBMD Project funded?</h3>
  <p>The majority of Free UK Genealogy's income comes from hosting advertising on our sites. A growing proportion comes from donations from our users - will you join them join them? You can make a Donation via <a href="https://test3.freebmd.org.uk/cms/donate" target="_blank"> the FreeBMD Page (opens in a new tab) </a> or <a href="https://www.freeukgenealogy.org.uk/help-us-keep-history-free" target="_blank"> the FreeUKGenealogy page (page opens in a new tab)</a>. </p>
  <p><mark> Note to reviewer: there are two hyperlinks here. Only a maximum of one <strong>may be needed</strong>. A Pay Icon is being created by another volunteer and it will be added to the right of the page (1/3rd column) in place of these hyperlinks</mark>. </p>
  
  <h3 id="correctEntries">Why doesn't FreeBMD correct errors in the GRO index?</h3>
   <p class="push-half--bottom">The objective of FreeBMD is to provide access to an online version of the GRO index and as such the FreeBMD policy is that the GRO index is transcribed <em>exactly</em> as it is. However, we recognise that there are errors in the index and a number of facilities are provided to address this:</p>
  <ul class="push-half--bottom">
     <li>transcribers can add Comments to the entries they transcribe, where they encounter issues in the index </li>
     <li>people searching the index can add Postems (notes) to entries in FreeBMD detailing errors they believe exist </li>
    <li>in exceptional cases, to aid searching the FreeBMD index, special System Entries may be added by FreeBMD, but these are clearly marked as being additions that are not in the original index </li>
  </ul>
  <p>In the case of a Postem, you can read an existing one or add one of your own from the expanded version of the Entry Information Page. (See for example, an image of the <a href="https://test3.freebmd.org.uk/cms/help/#orderCertificate">Entry Information page for Harry Clarke Dent</a> shown on our Help page). The line ‘More Information’ contains several symbols and the <strong>envelope symbol</strong> is for Postems. Selecting it, reloads the Entry Information page in its expanded form.</p>It is also possible for you to request that the GRO corrects their index. Contact <a href="http://www.gro.gov.uk/gro/content/certificates/contact_us.asp" target="_blank">the GRO with the appropriate information (opens in a new tab)</a>. When they agree the correction let us know  (via "Contact support") and we will annotate FreeBMD appropriately. 
  <p> Regrettably, the GRO has no method of informing the many holders of the index (both  online and physical) of corrections they make.</p>

  <h3 id="difficultToCorrect">How can I submit a correction? </h3>
   <p>Processing corrections takes a lot of effort and we need to ensure that we only investigate those corrections that comply with FreeBMD policies, particularly the policy <strong>of transcribing only what is in the GRO index</strong> (see <a href="#correctEntries">Why doesn't FreeBMD correct errors in the GRO index?</a>). Other corrections are handled by the use of Postems. Corrections are therefore automatically filtered to determine if they appear to comply with the instructions given on the corrections page.</p>
  <p class="islet islet--bordered">In order to simply the correction process, we have identified various reasons why researchers might wish to raise a query, or submit a correction; and, we have put them into a dropdown menu. This enables us to provide content-specific guidance. So, your first step is to use the dropdown menu to select your reason for contacting us about a particular entry. This gives you content-specific guidance and, if you wish to proceed, follow the steps given below.</p>
   <p class="push-half--bottom"><strong>In summary</strong> the process for submitting a correction is:</p>
     <ol class="push-half--bottom">
       <li>select the entry in the search results — which takes you to the Entry Information page </li>
       <li>select the <strong>Report an Error in this data</strong> — which takes you to a Data Problem Report page</li>
       <li>use the <em>Select your query</em> dropdown to select the most appropriate statement</li>
       <li>read the Explanation below that statement</li>
       <li><em>if you agree with the statement</em>: tick box to confirm that you have read it and wish to submit the report</li>
       <li>fill in your name and your email address — these are both mandatory</li>
       <li>fill in your statement of the problem, or your suggested correction (as appropriate) </li>
      <li>click Submit </li>
  </ol>
  <p class="push-half--bottom"><strong>Notes</strong>: the problem most people have with submitting corrections is failing to supply a valid <strong>Source</strong> or <strong>Reason</strong>. This happens because people do not comply with the instructions on the corrections page. The things people get wrong, since we know from past experience, is that just giving a simple statement of <em>what should be provided</em> does not work. The most common things people get wrong are:</p>
  <ul class="push-half--bottom">
     <li>adding unnecessary detail </li>
     <li>adding justification for the correction, rather than just identifying the source </li>
     <li>mentioning invalid sources (e.g., family information or other entries) </li>
  </ul>
  <h3 id="livingPersons">Can the FreeBMD database help me find a living person?</h3>
  <p>FreeBMD is a transcription of the GRO index and is of use for historical research. It is of very limited use for tracing living persons. We advise you to visit <a href="https://www.look4them.org.uk" target="_blank"> the UK web site: “look 4 them” (opens in a new Tab)</a>, which brings together six organizations who may be able to help.</p>
   <p> The Charity <a href="https://www.missingpeople.org.uk/" target="_blank"> “Missing People” provides support and guidance (opens in a new tab)</a>  for people who are missing, and those trying to find them, whether they have been missing for a few hours, or many years.</p>
  <p>Please bear in mind that a number of resources will charge for their services, whereas others are free. FreeBMD is also of limited use in finding if a person is still living due to our limited coverage of post-1980s Deaths. See charts of the&#160;<a href="https://www.freebmd.org.uk/progressD.shtml" target="_blank"> percentage coverage of Deaths by years on the original <strong>FreeBMD</strong> site (opens in a new tab)</a> for more information.</p>
   <p>If you are trying to trace your birth parents, the <a href="https://www.gov.uk/adoption-records" target="_blank">GRO’s Adoption records page (page opens in a new tab)</a> explains how to access <strong>your</strong> birth records. If you were adopted Wikitree's Adoption Angels are volunteers who may be able to help. See their <a href="https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Project:Adoption_Angels" target="_blank">Project: Adoption_Angels page (opens in a new tab)</a> for more information.</p>

  <h3 id="removeMyentry">Please can you remove my entry from FreeBMD</h3>
  <p>We can't remove entries. FreeBMD is a transcription of the <a href="#whyNecessary">GRO Index</a>, authorised by the GRO. The GRO Index of Births, Marriages and Deaths for England and Wales is publicly available information and as such it is not covered by the Data Protection Act 2018 (DPA 2018). In addition to FreeBMD, the GRO Index is accessible from a number of sources, both online and in person, and therefore exclusion from FreeBMD would have little effect with regard to concealment of the information.</p>
  <p>There is no facility for excluding entries and, indeed, it would be in violation of our accuracy commitment to do so. </p>
  <p>For further information please contact the <a href="https://www.gro.gov.uk/gro/content/certificates/contact_us.asp" target="_blank">GRO (opens in a new tab)</a>.</p>

